{
  "answer": "**Yājñavalkya Smṛti 2.135**, in Chapter 2 (\"On Legal Procedure\"), lists the sequential order of heirs for a sonless man (prior to 2.136, which states that each succeeding heir takes in the absence of the preceding): the wife, daughters, parents, brothers, their sons (i.e., nephews), kinsmen of the same *gotra*, cognate relations, a pupil, and a fellow-student.[^1]\n\nThis falls in section 8 on the \"Division of Heritage\" (*dāyavibhāgaprakaraṇam*), after discussing primary heirs like sons and appointed sons (e.g., 2.114–134).[^2]\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya, *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 2, [p-807a82](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-807a82).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya, *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 2, [p-c8fbd0](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/02/translation/#p-c8fbd0).",
